and it does a wonderful job humanizing the random enemies you spend the whole game slicing through like butter without being too blatantly preachy, although that scene comes very close to the line for me

I haven't played it recently enough to go too in depth on the themes but I really like how, much like the MGS saga, it condemns violence and shows how it ruins a person while acknowledging that sometimes violence IS necessary
early on when he fights Jetstream Sam, he loses because he sees his sword as a tool of justice "This is what happens when you bring a tool to a sword fight" Sam says, as he nearly kills him.

that he really does enjoy killing, and ultimately all of his justifications were a cope essentially. He still uses it for good so to speak but the game makes it clear that violence is more than just a means to an end even if you think of as one

Raiden starts the game explaining that it is necessary to use force to maintain peace, but at some point (I forget specifically when but it's in the latter half of the game I think) he embraces his inner demon which he had repressed since his time as a child soldier and realizes

some of the anti-war/muh freedom/America bad stuff is kinda cringe but it is a surprisingly thoughtful exploration of what living by the sword so to speak does to a person, even when it is for the right reasons
I never had a really high opinion of MGR besides the music but the more I think about the story, it does seem like a worthy entry in the Metal Gear franchise
